<paragraph blockId="7.[812,1420,1122,1527]" pageId="7" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,1334,1358]" pageId="7" pageNumber="330">Identification.</emphasis>
This river otter has dark brown-gray fur, which is lighter around the throat and snout, short legs, and long and rather stout tail. It is solitary and much smaller (
<quantity box="[971,1057,1435,1459]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="330" unit="kg" value="7.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="5.0">5–10 kg</quantity>
) than the social Giant River Otter (
<taxonomicName authority="(Zimmermann, 1780))" baseAuthorityName="Zimmermann" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[821,1316,1469,1493]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Pteronura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="330" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[821,1065,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="330">Pteronura brasiliensis</emphasis>
(Zimmermann, 1780))
</taxonomicName>
found in larger rivers farther north and east of our study area.
</paragraph>
